description.text:
Hi makers,

I thought you may like this other puzzle similar to my Dovetail Puzzle 1 but this time with a convex inner joint.

Print with minimum 100 micron layer height with about 20% infill. I use 3 outer shells and 6 top and bottom layers at 100 micron. The tollerances are quite tight so you need to have your printer dialed in. You will also need a 4mm dia 2mm thick disc magnet and a ~9mm pin (I used a section of an m4 screw cut and sanded to length). The disc magent is placed in the base, its a snugg fit so no need to glue but you can if you need to, and the m4 pin in the top section. Make sure this moves freely and does not stick out before you assemble it, otherwise you may struggle to get it apart.

Assembly is not difficult but you will need to offer the parts together at an unnatural angle (you will see what I mean).

Hope you enjoy this make.

title: X-UAV Mini Talon Parts v4 - Rear Gear Deck

description.text:
UPDATE 29 April, 2017
I added an optionsl screw plate and screw holes to the Rear_Deck_Pivot in case you want to make it completely removable.

The rear deck idea came from a poster on RCGroups as a way to mount an ESC directly under the hatch air vent. Of course you can also mount a GPS puck or RX if that suits your build. I really liked this idea so I came up with my own version which pivots up so you can get to anything below the deck if and when needed. Like my main "Gear Deck" in the v3 parts group, this mounts to the stock wood center structure. I do this because I think the wood is stronger than similar sized printed parts and this will fit any stock plane.

The front pivot piece snaps into the rear wood cross piece and is held there with glue (CA). The deck then helps to align where to glue the rear mount pieces.

Installation

  1. Print the "Complete STL group" file or the individual parts
  2. Tap the the two pivot ears to M3
  3. Tap the two rear mounts to M3
  4. Mount the deck to the pivot piece with two M3 x 8mm screws (I use nylon)
  5. Snap the pivot piece into the center of the rear structure wood cross-piece
  6. Wick in some thin CA glue.
  7. Pivot the deck to level and mark the side foam where the rear mounts are to go.
  8. Use E6000 or UHU-POR glue to glue the mounts in place and screw the deck down to hold it all together while the glue sets.

See Also
More Mini Talon parts - http://www.itsqv.com/QVM/index.php?title=Mini_Talon_Parts_Compilation

description.text:
This is an enclosure for one of the popular 4x4 keypad matrix boards that are widely available at low cost. Specifically, this is designed around the one that was included in HackerBoxes 0015, shown here. The board has no provisions for mounting and it's easy to short out the pins on the back of the board. Wrapping the board in this enclosure solves both problems neatly.

The enclosure consists of two 3D-printed plates that sandwich the board. The lower plate is flat on the bottom, and shaped on the top to support the circuit board in between the protruding component pins. The upper plate features close-fitting holes for each of the sixteen switches and clearance for the connector. Three tabs on the lower plate engage with matching slots on the upper plate to provide alignment. Four holes at the corners are provided to fit #2 or #4 screws to hold the sandwich together and mount it onto the front panel of your project. Alternatively, the sandwich may be glued together and the screws omitted.

The keypad matrix board comes with the connector on the top side. This connector may have straight pins, as shown here, or right angle pins. The top plate of this enclosure has clearance for either configuration. A cleaner design for a permanent installation would be to mount the connector on the reverse side; this enclosure would have to be modified to support that design.

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker 2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Infill:

20% (not critical)

Notes:

This example was printed in PLA at 50mm/s, 0.1mm layer height, 0.8mm shell thickness, with a raft. Cleanup would have been easier without the raft.

Both plates are flat on one side, and there are no overhangs at all. The top plate is flat on top, so it should be printed upside down.

None of the settings are likely to be critical. The square holes just have to fit around the sixteen switches.

Design Notes

This enclosure was designed in Fusion 360 based on measurements of one example of the circuit board. The enclosure does not fit tightly around the outside edges of the circuit board itself, since those edges may vary slightly from unit to unit. It does wrap snugly around the sixteen switch components, whose location is fixed relatively precisely by the circuit board's design. There's a good chance this enclosure will fit other 4x4 keypad matrix boards of similar design, but there's no guarantee.

The enclosure is designed larger than strictly necessary, in order to place the four screw holes symmetrically around the keypad. If front panel space is at a premium, the plates could be made only slightly bigger than the circuit board.

The Fusion 360 file includes a crude model of the circuit board itself, as a reference for designing the enclosure plates. The electrical pins on the switches are modeled as fat cylinders, representing an estimate of the clearance needed to avoid contact with the pin or its soldered joint. The connector is modeled as a simple box, including its own clearances.

Despite the mechanical clearances around the pins, this enclosure is not designed to work in an electrically conductive material. It would probably short out the switches where the pins are exposed on the top surface of the circuit board.

Take on the role of an antiques appraiser and research this artifact. Which president is associated with this artifact and what presidential power does it represent? The more information you provide, the more valuable the artifact.

This 3D printable model was created by a student in Ms. Relator's US Government class at Dominion HS in Virginia. Find out more about the Mystery Artifact lesson at https://www.lcps.org/Page/186358

Mystery artifact created by,
Faven Kennedy

1. The handshake on the back of the coin symbolized an agreement between two different groups of people in America.

  2. This item was redesigned during this president’s term.
  3. This was an item given to Native American chieftains from the American government as symbols of peace.

The Object: Peace Medal.

Details about the Object:
The coin has the side profile of a president with the word “peace” on top of it. On the back of the coin is a cane and a axe crossing each other, below that is two hands shaking. At the very bottom of the coin is the word, “friendship”.

President: Thomas Jefferson, 1801-1809, Democratic - Republican Party

Contribution & Presidential Role:
Jefferson assumed the role of chief diplomat when he sent a diplomatic mission to ensure peace treaties with the chiefs of multiple Native American tribes. The allocation of a new peace medal was supposed to send a message of renewed sense of mutual peace and an extension of friendship (thus the two hands on one side of the coin). Jefferson peace medals were first issued in 1801.

Impact on America/ Significance
Peace medals were an important part of our government's relations with Native Americans in the 18th and 19th centuries. Peace Medals were produced in silver for presentation to Native American chiefs and warriors. During Thomas Jefferson's management, a new style of peace medal was created which looked like those used by the British, and became the model for the rest of the series. Lewis and Clark took along three of the large Jefferson medals, 13 of the medium size, and 16 small medals which they presented to Native American chiefs along their route. Lewis and Clark were faithful about writing in their journals about events of each day, which included the distribution of medals. On May 11, 1806, Lewis noted: "Those with the likeness of Mr. Jefferson have all been thrown out (in the trash) except one of the largest size which we reserve for some great Chief on the Yellow rock river." (Mussulman, N.d.). These medals were used to secure peace treaties with Native Americans chieftains.

I wanted to research this president because I felt like the president was an extraordinary individual who had a profound impact in American history, especially when one takes into account his tremendous contribution authoring founding documents that supports American values and demonstrate independence till this day. However, it was also the smaller, less noticed things such as creating peace through tokens with Native Americans.

title: Extruder Light
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Have a problem seeing what you are printing? Need a way to get more light on your extruder nozzle? I always had to use a flashlight to try and follow the extruder nozzle around. Most of the time I was way to slow, by the time I moved the flashlight the nozzle had moved again. Finally decided to mount some LEDs near or on the extruder.

This is a remodeled blower mount with a place to hold a printed circuit board with three jumbo LEDs. The printed circuit board will also hold the 200 ohm LED current limiting resistor. All the inter-connecting wiring will be inside the shelled out area behind the printed circuit board. Power comes directly from the 12 volt power supply (or through a switch if you want)

Wanted:

  • More light
  • Always shining on nozzle edge
  • Not obstructing the view on the left side (I sit slightly off to the left side of the printer)

UPDATED 4/6/2017 For those of you that want to change from the existing blower fan to the typical 40 mm fan for part cooling, use new STL file: Blower mounting with LED mount with 40mm fan R1

Printer:

Migbot i3

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.2

Infill:

30%

Notes:

Laid the part on the blower side edge and printed the support under the printed circuit board holder.

Choose the LED angle bracket (45 or 60 degree) with the angle you think will give you the best LED light position on your nozzle. I used the 60 degree angle mounting block.

Assembly:

Bill of Materials:

  • Print (1) Blower mounting with LED mount (~ 1 hour)
  • Print (1) LED angle block 45 or 60 degree (~11 minutes)
  • Small piece of perf printed circuit board (~1 1/2" x 3" cut to fit mount)
  • (2) 6-32 x 3/8" machine screws
  • (2) 6-32 nuts
  • (3) jumbo LEDs
  • ~2 feet of black and red wire (can be other colors if you can keep track of the polarities).

Instructions
1). Print the two parts needed

2). Insert the (2) 6-32 nuts into the nut slots on the new blower mount

3). Cut small piece of perforated printed circuit board to fit on the bottom of the mount. Board will slide into the slot on one end and be held by (2) 6-32 machine screws on the other end.

4). Assemble the (3) LEDs into the angle block of your choice (45 or 60 degree).

5). Install the LED block on the printed circuit board and wire the three LEDs in series with the 200 Ohm current limiting resistor. Solder on a short Red and a short Black extension lead. See WORD document attached with schematic diagram

Test the wired LEDs with a 12 VDC source before finishing assembly

6). Install the assemble printed circuit board with the red & black leads coming out the small hole in the side of the blower mounting bracket. Use (2) 6-32 machine screws to hold the printed circuit board to the underside of the blower mounting bracket.

7). Mount the new blower mount with LEDs on the front of the extruder where the old blower mounting was. Depending on which side the extruder wiring is on, you may have rearrange that wiring a little. Reinstall your original blower motor.

8). Wire the red & black leads to the 12 volt power source that is always on.

I added some small strips of aluminum foil tape to the printed circuit board right next to the LEDs to act a a reflector.

Printers

This was originally designed for a Migbot i3 printer manufactured by Electron 3D. It should fit most other printers that have the X-axis mounted blower in front of the extruder motor (i.e. such as HICTOP or Anet printer).

title: Antenna mount for the OrangeRX OpenLRS transmitter module (JR 1W type)

description.text:
To mount a bigger antenna at a 90 degrees angle to the OrangeRX OpenRLS transmitter module (JR 1W type), I created this custom cover. The u.FL coax pigtail with the SMA connector is fastened in the right position for mounting a SRH-771 (or similar 433 MHz antenna). The inside of the antenna mount has the hexagonal nut shape cut out for this purpose.  
Note: The picture shows holes for the pin headers but I left them out in the final design as the pins are sitting too deep to be useful.  
Note 2: You need to reverse the handlebar on your radio for the antenna to fit. It's an easy mod, just unscrew the 2 nuts on the inside.

• Print flat on the platform with supports
  • Unscrew the original cover and remove the nut and washers from the SMA connector to free the coax cable
  • Insert coax cable in the printed antenna mount and fasten with washers and nut from the outside
    • Note: You need to reverse the handlebar on your radio for the antenna to fit. It's an easy mod, just unscrew the 2 nuts on the inside.

description.text:
It's the big debate: Anchor it to a flat surface, or set it up on a soft material. I imagine mounting it to a flat surface means you don't have to level the bed very often while setting it on a soft surface makes it run quieter. I don't have a flat surface I care to screw anything into, so the debate is settled for me: rubber feet.

These feet take 3mm thick standard o-rings (like what you put in your garden hose). I just happened to have a bag of them lying around. You can get them at a Walmart, Home Depot, Amazon (these look like they would do the trick), or any hardware store.

This design consists of four versions, each meant to pressure fit on different parts of the frame:

  • Version A - Fits to thick parts of the frame, such as the front of the bed.
  • Version B - Fits to thinner parts of the frame, such as the Y motor mounts.
  • Version C - Fits to two intersecting thick parts of the frame, such as where the back meets the sides.
  • Version D - Fits to two intersecting thick parts of the frame, but leaves a quadrant empty in case you have something mounted there. In my case, I have the Anet A8 Dual Mosfet & Motherboard Case with Reset Button, which takes up space in the lower left quadrant.

title: Faceted Bowl and Vase
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
When I designed this bowl and vase, I was going for a 'cut glass' look. These were both printed on my FlyingBear P902 printer with transparent PLA filaments. The bowl measures 165 mm dia. at the base, 196 mm dia. at the top, is 100 mm tall, and has a maximum diameter of 217 mm. The vase measures 56 mm dia. at the top and bottom, is 170 mm tall, and has a maximum diameter of 78.5 mm.

Note that the STL models are solid; that is, in the STL models, the bowl and vase are not hollowed out. To print them properly, you MUST use the 'spiralize' or 'vase-mode' settings in your slicer. This setting will not print any infill or top to the bowl or vase, but will print a bottom. (If you are not sure how to use the 'spiralize' or 'vase-mode' settings in your slicer, a search on Google will direct you to a number of instructional sites as well as videos.)

I used my 2012 copy of Alibre Design to create these models. For my slicer, I used Cura 2.4, which I am really growing to like.

With a maximum diameter of 217 mm, the bowl was really pushing the XY limits of my FlyingBear print area, which is 220 mm square. I found that my Cura slicer would not even try to slice the print until I disabled the skirt function under 'Build Plate Adhesion'. This is despite the fact that the size of the skirt (which would have been three lines, 3mm from the 165 mm diameter base) would have been well within the build plate area. To me, this appears to be a bug in the software.

Besides having the Cura 'spiralize' setting turned on, my layer height was 0.3 mm, my line width was 0.6 mm, and my bottom thickness was 0.9 mm (or three layers). To eliminate a z-hop bug that occurs when using 'spiralize' with Cura 2.4, I also set the 'Outer Wall Wipe Distance' to 0.

If your printer has a smaller build area than my FlyingBear (which is 220 x 220 x 270 mm), just scale the models down with your slicer so that they fit into your build area.

Another thing worthy of note is that one my first print of the vase, I increased my (usual) print speed from 60 mm/sec. to 80 mm/sec. I noticed that at this speed, the print looked OK, but the facets didn't seem as sharp as I would have liked. Also, there was a bit of 'ringing' in the facets as well. When I reduced my print speed back to 60 mm/sec., the facets looked significantly sharper, and the 'ringing' was much less evident. Also, the walls looked more transparent. As I am typing this, I am printing the vase at 40 mm/sec. to see how much it improves. So far, it is looking quite a bit better. It is possible that since I am using a transparent filament, these things might show up more than normal.

And who knows, maybe someday I will learn how to model something in my CAD software so that when I post it on Thingiverse, it wll not be lying on its side. But apparently, not today.

If anyone has any questions about either of these Things, please post them in the comments and I will do my best to answer.

title: The AMAZING  Corroscating Light Board !!

description.text:
I came up with this gift idea for my teenage daughter, a mini hand held "light board". Standard strip LEDs go along the entire diameter of a 220mm diameter piece of borosilicate 3D Printer glass (3mm thick, heat tempered glass - safety). It is best to set up an adjustable voltage power supply, to regulate brightness of the LEDs, which allows achieving the best glowing light effect when writing on the glass with Neon washable marker pens. Note there is a dimmer module included here, which uses an Arduino Pro Mini controller, which provides infinite possibilities. The power supply is 12V, readily availbe with the mating connector which has been integrated into the light board frame design. This light board is useful in many ways, as a toy, a family message board, or even a night light with a message!

The Light Board pictured here, was built using PLA Wood (Hatchbox), stained with wood stain and several coats of Shellac over that stain (don't use Urethane, it will not harden, since wood stain doesn't fully absorb into the material).

The frame is designed to accept a 12V power supply with 2.1x5.5mm plug connector, like this one:
https://www.amazon.com/Adapter-100-240V-Transformers-Switching-Adaptor/dp/B019Q3U72M/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1491435387&sr=8-1&keywords=12V+Power+Supply+Adapter+and+2.1mm+x+5.5mm+DC+Connector

Power Controller components include:

5-35V 3W LED Driver 700mA PWM dimming DC to DC buck
Arduino Pro Mini
Large momentary push button switch

LEDs used: LED White Light Strip 1M 30/M 3528 Patch

If there is some interest, judged by views / comments here .. I will post a more detailed Bill of Materials with links to items, and assist makers in building their own.
